URL processing functions. See implementation in separate .cpp files. All functions are not strictly follow RFC, instead they are maximally simplified for performance reasons.

Functions for extraction parts of URL. If URL has nothing like, then empty string is returned.

domain domain\+Without\+WWW top\+Level\+Domain protocol path query\+String fragment query\+String\+And\+Fragment netloc

Functions, removing parts from URL. If URL has nothing like, then it is returned unchanged.

cut\+WWW cut\+Fragment cut\+Query\+String cut\+Query\+String\+And\+Fragment

Extract value of parameter in query string or in fragment identifier. Return empty string, if URL has no such parameter. If there are many parameters with same name -\/ return value of first one. \mbox{\hyperlink{structdoris_1_1vectorized_1_1_value}{Value}} is not \%-\/decoded.

extract\+URLParameter(\+URL, name)

Extract all parameters from URL in form of array of strings name=value. extract\+URLParameters(\+URL)

Extract names of all parameters from URL in form of array of strings. extract\+URLParameter\+Names(\+URL)

Remove specified parameter from URL. cut\+URLParameter(\+URL, name)

Used to interpret expressions in a set in IN, and also in the query of the form INSERT ... VALUES ...

To work correctly with expressions of the form {\ttfamily 1.\+0 IN (1)} or, for example, {\ttfamily 1 IN (1, 2.\+0, 2.\+5, -\/1)} work the same way as {\ttfamily 1 IN (1, 2)}. Checks for the compatibility of types, checks values fall in the range of valid values of the type, makes type conversion. If the value does not fall into the range -\/ returns \mbox{\hyperlink{structdoris_1_1vectorized_1_1_null}{Null}}. NULL remains NULL after any conversion.函数调用图\+:

{\footnotesize\ttfamily bool build\+\_\+histogram (\begin{DoxyParamCaption}\item[{std\+::vector$<$ \mbox{\hyperlink{structdoris_1_1vectorized_1_1_bucket}{Bucket}}$<$ \mbox{\hyperlink{exp_8c_a0acb682b8260ab1c60b918599864e2e5}{T}} $>$ $>$ \&}]{buckets,  }\item[{const std\+::map$<$ \mbox{\hyperlink{exp_8c_a0acb682b8260ab1c60b918599864e2e5}{T}}, size\+\_\+t $>$ \&}]{ordered\+\_\+map,  }\item[{const size\+\_\+t}]{max\+\_\+num\+\_\+buckets }\end{DoxyParamCaption})}

Greedy equi-\/height histogram construction algorithm, inspired by the My\+SQL equi\+\_\+height implementation(\href{https://dev.mysql.com/doc/dev/mysql-server/latest/equi__height_8h.html}{\texttt{ https\+://dev.\+mysql.\+com/doc/dev/mysql-\/server/latest/equi\+\_\+\+\_\+height\+\_\+8h.\+html}}).

Given an ordered collection of \mbox{[}value, count\mbox{]} pairs and a maximum bucket size, construct a histogram by inserting values into a bucket while keeping track of its size. If the insertion of a value into a non-\/empty bucket causes the bucket to exceed the maximum size, create a new empty bucket and continue.

The algorithm guarantees a selectivity estimation error of at most $\sim$2 $\ast$ \#values / \#buckets, often less. Values with a higher relative frequency are guaranteed to be placed in singleton buckets.

The minimum composite bucket size is used to minimize the worst case selectivity estimation error. In general, the algorithm will adapt to the data distribution to minimize the size of composite buckets. The heavy values can be placed in singleton buckets and the remaining values will be evenly spread across the remaining buckets, leading to a lower composite bucket size.

Note\+: The term \char`\"{}value\char`\"{} refers to an entry in a column and the actual value of an entry. The ordered\+\_\+map is an ordered collection of \mbox{[}distinct value, value count\mbox{]} pairs. For example, a Value\+\_\+map$<$\+String$>$ could contain the pairs \mbox{[}\char`\"{}a\char`\"{}, 1\mbox{]}, \mbox{[}\char`\"{}b\char`\"{}, 2\mbox{]} to represent one \char`\"{}a\char`\"{} value and two \char`\"{}b\char`\"{} values.


\begin{DoxyParams}{参数}
{\em buckets} & A vector of empty buckets that will be populated with data. \\
\hline
{\em ordered\+\_\+map} & An ordered map of distinct values and their counts. \\
\hline
{\em max\+\_\+num\+\_\+buckets} & The maximum number of buckets that can be used.\\
\hline
\end{DoxyParams}
\begin{DoxyReturn}{返回}
True if the buckets were successfully built, false otherwise. 
\end{DoxyReturn}

\doxysubsubsection{\texorpdfstring{EmptyPODArraySize}{EmptyPODArraySize}}
{\footnotesize\ttfamily constexpr size\+\_\+t Empty\+PODArray\+Size = 1024\hspace{0.3cm}{\ttfamily [static]}, {\ttfamily [constexpr]}}

A dynamic array for POD types. Designed for a small number of large arrays (rather than a lot of small ones). To be more precise -\/ for use in \mbox{\hyperlink{classdoris_1_1vectorized_1_1_column_vector}{Column\+Vector}}. It differs from std\+::vector in that it does not initialize the elements.

Made noncopyable so that there are no accidential copies. You can copy the data using {\ttfamily assign} method.

Only part of the std\+::vector interface is supported.

The default constructor creates an empty object that does not allocate memory. Then the memory is allocated at least initial\+\_\+bytes bytes.

If you insert elements with push\+\_\+back, without making a {\ttfamily reserve}, then \mbox{\hyperlink{classdoris_1_1vectorized_1_1_p_o_d_array}{PODArray}} is about 2.\+5 times faster than std\+::vector.

The template parameter {\ttfamily pad\+\_\+right} -\/ always allocate at the end of the array as many unused bytes. Can be used to make optimistic reading, writing, copying with unaligned SIMD instructions.

The template parameter {\ttfamily pad\+\_\+left} -\/ always allocate memory before 0th element of the array (rounded up to the whole number of elements) and zero initialize -\/1th element. It allows to use -\/1th element that will have value 0. This gives performance benefits when converting an array of offsets to array of sizes.

Some methods using allocator have TAllocator\+Params variadic arguments. These arguments will be passed to corresponding methods of TAllocator. Example\+: pointer to \mbox{\hyperlink{classdoris_1_1vectorized_1_1_arena}{Arena}}, that is used for allocations.

Why \mbox{\hyperlink{class_allocator}{Allocator}} is not passed through constructor, as it is done in C++ standard library? Because sometimes we have many small objects, that share same allocator with same parameters, and we must avoid larger object size due to storing the same parameters in each object. This is required for states of aggregate functions.

\mbox{\hyperlink{classdoris_1_1vectorized_1_1_p_o_d_array}{PODArray}} does not have memset 0 when allocating memory, therefore, the query mem tracker is virtual memory, which will cause the query memory statistics to be higher than the actual physical memory.
